This page is a supplementary teaching scaffold for tokenization.

## Core concept

A tokenizer converts characters into located token kinds. It recognises spelling and delimiters without deciding program meaning.

## Beanstalk boundary

Tokenization owns:

- lexical recognition
- source locations
- string and template delimiter context
- numeric text scanning
- spacing diagnostics that are lexical
- directive token recognition through the supplied registry

It does not resolve imports, types, declarations or target support.

Beanstalk source kinds may choose different starting lexical contexts. Normal `.bst` starts in code. Beandown starts inside an implicit template body. Plain Markdown uses its own preparation path.

## Rewrite focus

Explain why token boundaries are separated from parsing, how precise locations improve diagnostics and why shared numeric grammar does not move numeric semantics into the tokenizer.

Canonical details live in `docs/compiler-design-overview.md`.
